' Association|PFA Player of the Month]]: November 2019<ref name=\"PFA\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Liga MX player|75425}}\n* {{MedioTiempo|raul-alonso-jimenez-rodriguez}}\n* [http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/futbol/jugador/_/id/167060 Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez] at [[ESPN Deportes]] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{FIFA}}\n* {{IOC profile|raul-jimenez}}\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|ji/raul-jimenez-1|Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez|archive=20161203093240}}\n* {{Soccerbase|69582}}\n\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Mexico squads\n|bg = #016549\n|fg = White\n|bordercolor =#CE1126\n|list1=\n{{Mexico men's football squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Mexico squad 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Mexico squad 2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Mexico squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Mexico squad 2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Mexico squad Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario}}\n{{Mexico squad 2017 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Mexico squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Mexico squad 2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{Ta\u00e7a da Liga top scorers}}\n{{CONCACAF Awards}}\n{{CONCACAF Gold Cup awards}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jimenez, Raul}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Hidalgo (state)]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Mexican footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Am\u00e9rica footballers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Mexico youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexico international footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:2013 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario players]]\n[[Category:2017 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Mexico]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:CONCACAF Gold Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Mexican expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Mexican expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Mexican expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Mexican expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican association football player}}\n{{About|the Mexican footballer|the Argentine singer|Ra\u00fal Gim\u00e9nez}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Spanish name|Jim\u00e9nez|Rodr\u00edguez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez\n| image = Raul Jim\u00e9nez.png\n| caption = Jim\u00e9nez with [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in 2017\n| full_name = Ra\u00fal Alonso Jim\u00e9nez Rodr\u00edguez<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/844127 |title=2018/19 Premier League squads confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=3 September 2018 |access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1991|5|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Tepeji]], [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]], Mexico\n| height = 1.90 m<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez |url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/team/first-team/ra\u00fal-jim\u00e9nez/ |website=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. |access-date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Forward|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| youthyears1 = 2008\u20132011\n| youthclubs1 = [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]\n| years1 = 2011\u20132014\n| clubs1 = [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]\n| caps1 = 96\n| goals1 = 36\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps2 = 21\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2015\u20132019\n| clubs3 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n| caps3 = 80\n| goals3 = 18\n| years4 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 38\n| goals4 = 13\n| years5 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs5 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n| caps5 = 29\n| goals5 = 13\n| nationalyears1 = 2012\n| nationalteam1 = [[Mexico national under-23 football team|Mexico U23]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 13\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2013\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 81\n| nationalgoals2 = 24\n| club-update = 16:09, 1 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 19 November 2019\n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|MEX}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2019 United States]]|[[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup squads#Mexico|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Ra\u00fal Alonso Jim\u00e9nez Rodr\u00edguez''' ({{IPA-es|ra\u02c8ul xi\u02c8menes|am}}; born 5 May 1991) is a Mexican professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for Premier League club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]]. \n\nHe began his career in [[Club Am\u00e9rica]]'s [[Club Am\u00e9rica Reserves|youth system]] before debuting in the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|first division]] in October 2011. He won his first championship with Am\u00e9rica in 2013, winning the [[2012\u201313 Liga MX season#Clausura|Clausura]] tournament, and was the team's second-highest goalscorer. In August 2014, Jim\u00e9nez joined Spanish side [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]. After one season, he signed for [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], with whom he won two consecutive [[Primeira Liga|league]] titles, among other major honours.\n\nJim\u00e9nez was a part of the [[Mexico national under-23 football team|Mexican squad]] that won the gold medal at the [[Summer Olympics]] in [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mexico's breath of fresh air |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/newsid=2116453/ |publisher=[[FIFA]] |access-date=23 June 2013}}</ref> A full international since 2013, Jim\u00e9nez has represented his country at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]] and [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], the [[2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2013]] and [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013]] and [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]], the [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], and the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Am\u00e9rica===\n====2011\u201312 season====\nJim\u00e9nez began his career playing for [[Club Am\u00e9rica]]'s [[Club Am\u00e9rica Reserves|youth system]], being considered a promising young striker. On 9 October 2011, under interim-coach [[Alfredo Tena]], Jim\u00e9nez made his professional debut during the [[2011\u201312 Club Am\u00e9rica season#Apertura|Apertura]] tournament against [[Monarcas Morelia]], in a match which ended in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web |last=Alcibvia |first=Rafael |title=Am\u00e9rica 1-1 Morelia\u2026 Las \u00c1guilas se alejaron de la calificaci\u00f3n |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2011/10/09/america-1-1-morelia-las-aguilas-se-alejaron-de-la-calificacion_35689 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=9 October 2011}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 30 October in a 2\u20133 loss to [[Puebla FC|Puebla]], scoring in the 2nd minute of the match.<ref>{{cite web |last=Alcivia |first=Rafael |title=Am\u00e9rica 2-3 Puebla... Las \u00c1guilas se despidieron del Azteca con derrota |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2011/10/30/america-2-3-puebla-las-aguilas-se-despidieron-del-azteca-con-derrota_35725 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=30 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031173139/http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2011/10/30/america-2-3-puebla-las-aguilas-se-despidieron-del-azteca-con-derrota_35725 |archive-date=31 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> He appeared six times and scored one goal in his debut tournament.\n\nJim\u00e9nez did not appear in the [[2011\u201312 Club Am\u00e9rica season#Clausura|Clausura 2012]] until 11 February\u2014week seven of the tournament\u2014against [[Club Atlas|Atlas]], which ended in a 1\u20131 draw, coming on as a second-half substitute for [[Christian Berm\u00fadez]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Garrido |first=Jos\u00e9 Maria |title=Atlas 1-1 Am\u00e9rica... H\u00famedo empate en el Jalisco |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/02/11/atlas-1-1-america-humedo-empate-en-el-jalisco_40030 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=11 February 2012}}</ref> He scored his first goal of the tournament on 9 March in the 1\u20131 draw against [[Club Tijuana|Tijuana]] at the [[Estadio Caliente]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Zamora |first=Jessica |title=Tijuana 1-1 Am\u00e9rica... Con nueve, Xolos rescat\u00f3 empate ante el \u00c1guila |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/03/09/tijuana-1-1-america-con-nueve-xolos-rescato-empate-ante-el-aguila_40066 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=9 March 2012}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez appeared twelve times and scored once during the Clausura, with Am\u00e9rica being eliminated in the semi-finals by [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]].\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nAfter participating in the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] with [[Mexico national under-23 football team|Mexico]] and the sale of [[Vicente Mat\u00edas Vuoso]], Jim\u00e9nez won a spot in Am\u00e9rica's starting eleven for the [[2012\u201313 Club Am\u00e9rica season#Apertura|Apertura 2012]] tournament, playing as a second-striker alongside [[Christian Ben\u00edtez]] in manager [[Miguel Herrera]]'s 5-3-2 tactical scheme. He was also given the vacant number 9 shirt, switching from the number 47 shirt he debuted with. Jim\u00e9nez scored on 15 September in the 2\u20130 victory over [[Santos Laguna]] at the [[Estadio Azteca]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Malag\u00f3n |first=Edgar |title=Am\u00e9rica 2-0 Santos... \u00c1guilas abollan corona del Campe\u00f3n |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/09/15/america-2-0-santos-aguilas-abollan-corona-del-campeon_41323 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=15 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918193140/http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/09/15/america-2-0-santos-aguilas-abollan-corona-del-campeon_41323 |archivedate=18 September 2012 }}</ref> He would go on to score two weeks later in the 1\u20131 draw against Monarcas Morelia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Montes |first=Jose Mart\u00edn |title=Am\u00e9rica 1-1 Morelia... Ninguno convence |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/09/29/america-1-1-morelia-ninguno-convence_41342 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=29 September 2012}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez received his first red card during Am\u00e9rica's 2\u20131 victory over [[San Luis F.C.|San Luis]], meaning he would miss ''[[El S\u00faper Cl\u00e1sico (Mexico)|El S\u00faper Cl\u00e1sico]]'' against [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ter\u00e1n |first=Jose Manuel |title=San Luis 1-2 Am\u00e9rica... 'Chucho' Ben\u00edtez regres\u00f3 y el \u00c1guila vol\u00f3 |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/10/02/san-luis-1-2-america-chucho-benitez-regreso-y-el-aguila-volo_41353 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=2 October 2012}}</ref> On 3 November, he scored the second goal in the 4\u20130 win over [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ter\u00e1n |first=Jose Manuel |title=Am\u00e9rica 4-0 Pachuca... 'Chucho' destroz\u00f3 las esperanzas tuzas |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/11/03/america-4-0-pachuca-chucho-destrozo-las-esperanzas-tuzas_41395 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=3 November 2012}}</ref> On 17 November, Jim\u00e9nez scored in the 1\u20132 defeat to Morelia in the second-leg of the quarter-final. Despite the loss, Am\u00e9rica won the series by a 3\u20132 aggregate score and advanced to the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |last=Montes |first=Juan Mart\u00edn |title=Am\u00e9rica (3)1-2(2) Morelia... Clasificaci\u00f3n dram\u00e1tica |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2012/11/17/america-3-1-2-2-morelia-clasificacion-dramatica_44693 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=17 November 2012}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica would ultimately be eliminated in the semi-finals by [[Club Toluca|Toluca]]. Jimen\u00e9z ended the tournament with sixteen appearances and scoring four goals.\n\nJim\u00e9nez began the [[2012\u201313 Club Am\u00e9rica season#Clausura|Clausura 2013]] tournament as a starter in the first two league matches, and scored his first [[brace (sports)|brace]] in the 4\u20130 victory over [[C.F. Atlante|Atlante]] on 19 January.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ter\u00e1n |first=Jose Manuel |title=Am\u00e9rica 4-0 Atlante... \u00c1guilas de hierro |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2013/01/19/america-4-0-atlante-aguilas-de-hierro_44848 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=19 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121133301/http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2013/01/19/america-4-0-atlante-aguilas-de-hierro_44848 |archivedate=21 January 2013 }}</ref> He bagged another brace on 2 February in Am\u00e9rica's 3\u20130 win against [[Quer\u00e9taro F.C.|Quer\u00e9taro]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Regresa Am\u00e9rica al triunfo y sin esforzarse vence 3-0 a Quer\u00e9taro |url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/futbol/cronica?id=358800 |publisher=ESPN Deportes |language=Spanish |access-date=2 February 2013}}</ref> On 31 March, Jim\u00e9nez scored two headers in the 2\u20130 victory over Guadalajara at the [[Estadio Omnilife]].<ref>{{cite web |last=McCauley |first=Kevin |title=Chivas Guadalajara vs. Club Am\u00e9rica, 2013 Super Clasico: Final score 0-2, Goats crumble |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2013/3/31/4168952/chivas-vs-america-2013-super-clasico-final-score-result |publisher=SB Nation |access-date=31 March 2013}}</ref> Jimen\u00e9z finished the regular phase of the tournament with eight goals, and scored in Am\u00e9rica's 1\u20130 away win over [[Club Universidad Nacional|Pumas UNAM]] in the first-leg of the quarter-final series of the playoffs on 8 May.<ref>{{cite web |last=Collazo |first=Jonathan |title=Am\u00e9rica vuela otra vez ante Pumas, ahora en Liguilla |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2013/05/08/america-vuela-otra-vez-ante-pumas-ahora-en-liguilla_46933 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=8 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606223702/http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2013/05/08/america-vuela-otra-vez-ante-pumas-ahora-en-liguilla_46933 |archive-date=6 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the second-leg of the semi-final series against Monterrey, Jimen\u00e9z scored from a [[penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] and assisted Christian Benitez in the second goal to win the match 2\u20131 (4\u20133 on aggregate), sending Am\u00e9rica to the [[2013 Liga MX Clausura Liguilla#Final|Final]] against [[Cruz Azul]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Am\u00e9rica vence 2-1 a Monterrey y 'vuela' a la final del futbol mexicano |url=http://mexico.cnn.com/deportes/2013/05/18/america-monterrey-liguilla-semifinal-futbol |publisher=CNN M\u00e9xico |language=Spanish |access-date=18 May 2013}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez played in both legs and scored in the subsequent penalty shoot-out which Am\u00e9rica ultimately won, thus being crowned league champions.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u00a1Am\u00e9rica es Campe\u00f3n de la Liga MX! |url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=8847 |website=Club Am\u00e9rica |language=Spanish |access-date=27 May 2013}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nOn 3 August 2013 Jim\u00e9nez scored his first goal of the [[2013\u201314 Liga MX season|Apertura]] tournament in the 3\u20130 win over Atlas.<ref>{{cite web |title=Am\u00e9rica 3-0 Atlas: Las \u00c1guilas homenajearon con goles a 'Chucho' Ben\u00edtez |url=http://futbol.univision.com/article/1625289/2013-08-03/mexico/america-3-0-atlas-cronica-jornada-4-liga-mx |website=Univision|language=Spanish |access-date=3 August 2013}}</ref> He would go on to score in the following three-consecutive matches in wins over [[Atlante FC|Atlante]], Pachuca, and Morelia, respectively, taking his goal tally to four goals in five matches played. He would score again on 13 September in Am\u00e9rica's 1\u20132 defeat to Santos Laguna.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ruiz |first=Alberto |date=13 September 2013 |title=Santos freno el vuel\u00f3 del ave |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2013/09/13/santos-freno-el-vuelo-del-ave_47459 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=13 September 2013}}</ref> On 5 October, Jim\u00e9nez scored a header and assisted in [[Luis Gabriel Rey]]'s goal in the 2\u20130 victory over Guadalajara.<ref>{{cite web |last=McCauley |first=Kevin |date=5 October 2013 |title=Club America vs. Chivas Guadalajara: Final score 2-0, Raul Jimenez the Super Eagles' hero |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2013/10/5/4807156/america-vs-chivas-2013-super-clasico-final-score-result-liga-mx |publisher=SB Nation |access-date=5 October 2013}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez ended the regular-phase of the Apertura with seven goals in twelve games played. He scored in the second-leg of the quarter-finals against [[Tigres UANL]] which ended in a 1\u20131 draw at the Estadio Azteca on 1 December, with Am\u00e9rica advancing, despite a 2\u20132 aggregate score, due to the away-goals rule.<ref>{{cite web |title=Am\u00e9rica 1-1 Tigres |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/ficha.php?id_partido=51025 |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=1 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206035430/http://www.mediotiempo.com/ficha.php?id_partido=51025 |archivedate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> Am\u00e9rica would win the semi-final matches against Toluca and advance once again to the league final, though failing to achieve the repeat after losing both legs to [[Club Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Contreras Legaspi |first=Carlos |date=15 December 2013 |title=Le\u00f3n, campe\u00f3n del Apertura 2013 |url=http://laaficion.milenio.com/futbol/Espiritu-campeon_0_208779160.html |website=La Afici\u00f3n |publisher=Grupo Milenio |language=Spanish |access-date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2013\u201314 Liga MX season#Clausura|Clausura 2014]] tournament saw Jim\u00e9nez make 17 appearances and score 8 goals.<ref>{{Medio Tiempo|raul-alonso-jimenez}}</ref> In the quarter-final match against [[Club Santos Laguna|Santos Laguna]] on 30 April, Jim\u00e9nez scored a hat-trick in the 5\u20133 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/ficha.php?id_partido=53431 |title=Am\u00e9rica 5 - 3 Santos - mediotiempo.com |date=30 April 2014 |work=mediotiempo.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505130205/http://www.mediotiempo.com/ficha.php?id_partido=53431 |archivedate=5 May 2014 }}</ref> However, Am\u00e9rica would lose the second-leg of the series 1\u20133 and being eliminated from the playoffs, despite a 6\u20136 aggregate score due to the away-goals rule.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/ficha.php?id_partido=53435 |title=Santos 3 - 1 Am\u00e9rica - mediotiempo.com |date=3 May 2014 |work=mediotiempo.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508162218/http://www.mediotiempo.com/ficha.php?id_partido=53435 |archivedate=8 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nJim\u00e9nez began the [[2014\u201315 Liga MX season|Apertura 2014]] tournament scoring four goals in the first three games. On 26 July, he scored the first goal in Am\u00e9rica's 2\u20131 win over Tijuana. On 4 August, he scored a hat-trick and assisted [[Oribe Peralta]] in the 4\u20130 win against [[Puebla F.C.|Puebla]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ligamx.net/home/noticia.html?id=8232 |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808055152/http://www.ligamx.net/home/noticia.html?id=8232 |archivedate=8 August 2014 }}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez played his final game for Am\u00e9rica on 9 August 2014 against Tigres UANL, providing the assist for the second goal scored by [[Miguel Lay\u00fan]] in the 2\u20130 win.\n\n===Atl\u00e9tico Madrid===\n[[File:Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez DEP-ATM 045 1200.jpg|thumb|250px|Jim\u00e9nez (no. 11) playing for [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2015]]\nOn 13 August 2014, [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] reached an agreement with Club Am\u00e9rica for Jim\u00e9nez,<ref>{{cite news |title=Agreement with Am\u00e9rica for the transfer of Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez |url=http://en.clubatleticodemadrid.com/noticias/agreement-with-america-for-the-transfer-of-raul-jimenez |publisher=[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] |date=13 August 2014 |access-date=14 August 2014}}</ref> for a fee reported to be in the region of \u20ac11&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |title=El Atl\u00e9tico ficha a Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez |trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico signs Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez |url=http://www.marca.com/2014/08/12/futbol/equipos/atletico/1407844236.html |newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |language=es |date=12 August 2014 |access-date=14 August 2014}}</ref> The following day, he signed a six-year deal after passing the medical examination.<ref>{{cite news |title=Welcome Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez |url=http://en.clubatleticodemadrid.com/noticias/welcome-raul-jimenez |publisher=[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] |date=14 August 2014 |access-date=12 September 2014}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez made his debut on 16 August, in the final of the [[Ram\u00f3n de Carranza Trophy]] pre-season tournament against [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], starting the match and being substituted out in the 79th minute. Atl\u00e9tico won 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez gan\u00f3 primer titulo con el 'Atleti' |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/libertadores/noticias/2014/08/16/raul-jimenez-gano-primer-titulo-con-el-atleti |publisher=Medio Tiempo |language=Spanish |access-date=16 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817180737/http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/libertadores/noticias/2014/08/16/raul-jimenez-gano-primer-titulo-con-el-atleti |archivedate=17 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\nJim\u00e9nez made his competitive debut in the first leg of the [[2014 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]] on 19 August, a 1\u20131 draw against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], playing the final 12 minutes in place of fellow debutant [[Mario Mand\u017euki\u0107]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Spanish Super Copa: Real Madrid and Atletico draw 1\u20131 in first leg |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/325067/report |access-date=20 August 2014 |work=[[Sky Sports News]] |date=19 August 2014}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez played in the second leg as well coming in as a substitute for [[Antoine Griezmann]] in the 73rd minute of the match, the game ended in a 1\u20130 win and an aggregated score of 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jenson |first=Peter |date=22 August 2014 |title=Atletico Madrid 1-0 Real Madrid (agg 2-1): Cristiano Ronaldo, Gareth Bale and James Rodriguez fail to fire as quickfire Mario Mandzukic secures Spanish Super Cup for Diego Simeone |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2732278/Atletico-Madrid-1-0-Real-Madrid-agg-2-1-Cristiano-Ronaldo-Gareth-Bale-James-Rodriguez-fail-fire-quickfire-Mario-Mandzukic-secures-Spanish-Super-Cup-Diego-Simeone.html |work=[[Daily Mail]] |access-date=22 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nJim\u00e9nez made his [[2014\u201315 La Liga|La Liga]] debut on 25 August 2014, in a goalless draw against [[Rayo Vallecano]]. He scored his first league goal for Atl\u00e9tico on 27 September, in a 4\u20130 win against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], coming off the bench. It was his only goal for Atl\u00e9tico that season.<ref name=\"soccerway\">{{Soccerway|access-date=7 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Benfica===\nOn 9 August 2015 Jim\u00e9nez, who was expected to complete a loan deal to [[Premier League]] side [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]], failed to show up to his medical after reports claimed he had missed his flight to [[London]] after he had overslept.<ref name=\"westham\">{{cite news |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez overslept and missed West Ham medical |url=http://as.com/diarioas/2015/08/09/english/1439150331_086804.html |newspaper=[[Diario AS]] |access-date=14 August 2015 |date=9 August 2015}}</ref> However, multiple sources had reported his agent [[Jorge Mendes]] had suggested he spurn the move, in favour of a move to [[Primeira Liga]] side [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]].<ref name=westham />\n\nOn 13 August 2015, Jim\u00e9nez joined Portuguese champions Benfica, signing a five-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slbenfica.pt/noticias/detalhedenoticia/tabid/2788/ArticleId/42641/language/pt-PT/.aspx |title=Mostrar que posso ajudar a equipa |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Show that I can help the team |date=13 August 2015 |publisher=[[S.L. Benfica]] |access-date=13 August 2015}}</ref> Benfica spent \u20ac9.836&nbsp;million to bring Jim\u00e9nez to the club, although this included unspecified amounts on agent's fees and signing-on fees in addition to the transfer fee itself.<ref name=\"Prospeto de oferta p\u00fablica...\">{{cite web |url=http://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi/emitentes/docs/fsd150611.pdf#66 |date=14 April 2016 |title=Prospeto de oferta p\u00fablica |website=CMVM |language=Portuguese |format=PDF |page=66 |access-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> The \u20ac9.836&nbsp;million may have included a \u20ac1&nbsp;million transfer fee, and \u20ac3&nbsp;million to acquire 50% of the player's economic rights.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mexico striker Raul Jimenez reaches deal to join Benfica |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/2561904/mexicos-raul-jimenez-reaches-deal-to-join-benfica |publisher=[[ESPN FC]] |access-date=14 August 2015 |date=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\n[[File:Zen-benf16 (1).jpg|thumb|Jim\u00e9nez playing for [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League]]]]\nJim\u00e9nez scored his first goal for Benfica on 29 August against [[Moreirense]], scoring a header in the 75th minute to level the score 1\u20131, with Benfica eventually winning the match 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web |title=Benfica fights back for 3-2 win over Moreirense |url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/benfica-fights-back-for-3-2-win-over-moreirense-082915 |website=Fox Sports |access-date=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November, Jim\u00e9nez scored his first two goals in the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], striking at both ends in each half as Benfica salvaged a 2\u20132 away draw against [[FC Astana|Astana]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Benfica fight back to eliminate Astana |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000634/match=2015742/postmatch/report/index.html |website=Uefa.com |access-date=25 November 2015}}</ref> On 9 March 2016, he helped Benfica to reach the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|quarter-finals]] of the Champions League in a 2\u20131 away victory against [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]]. In the 85th minute of the match, Jimen\u00e9z struck a long-range shot which was saved by [[Yuri Lodygin]] onto the bar, with the ball rebounding to [[Nicol\u00e1s Gait\u00e1n]] who tied the match 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |date=9 March 2016 |title=Zenit St Petersburg 1-2 Benfica (1-3 agg) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35758921 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=van Poortvliet |first=Richard |date=9 March 2016 |title=Benfica's Zenit late show wins quarter-final spot |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000635/match=2015769/postmatch/report/index.html |website=UEFA |access-date=9 March 2016}}</ref> On 9 April, he came off the bench and scored the winning goal in the 2\u20131 victory against [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Coimbra \u2013 O.A.F.|Acad\u00e9mica]], securing Benfica's lead in the [[2015\u201316 Primeira Liga|Primeira Liga]].<ref>{{cite news |date=9 April 2016 |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez da triunfo al Benfica y lo mantiene como l\u00edder |trans-title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez gives the victory to Benfica who remain in lead |url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/adrenalina/2016/04/09/1085543 |language=Spanish |newspaper=Exc\u00e9lsior |access-date=10 April 2016}}</ref> Four days later, due to the suspension of [[Jonas Gon\u00e7alves Oliveira|Jonas]] in the first leg, Jim\u00e9nez started the second leg of the Champions League quarter-final match against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], scoring the first goal in the 2\u20132 draw at the [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz]]; a 3\u20132 defeat on aggregate meant Benfica were eliminated from the competition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benfica 2-2 Bayern Munich |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36020598 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April, he scored another winner in the league, this time scoring the lone goal against [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]], extending Benfica's lead in the league.<ref>{{cite news |last=Castro |first=Gaspar |date=24 April 2016 |title=Jim\u00e9nez lan\u00e7a o Benfica de volta para o topo |trans-title=Jim\u00e9nez puts Benfica back into the lead |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira_liga/artigo/2016/04/24/jimenez-lanca-o-benfica-de-volta-para-o-topo |language=Portuguese |website=SAPO Desporto |access-date=10 May 2016}}</ref> On 15 May, Jim\u00e9nez came on as a second-half substitute as Benfica were crowned league champions after defeating [[Clube Desportivo Nacional|Nacional]] 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez, campe\u00f3n con el Benfica |trans-title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez, champion with Benfica |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/internacional/cronicas/2016/05/15/raul-jimenez-campeon-con-el-benfica_65519 |language=Spanish |website=Medio Tiempo |access-date=15 May 2016}}</ref> Five days later, he capped off the [[2015\u201316 S.L. Benfica season|season]] scoring from the penalty spot in the 6\u20132 win over [[C.S. Mar\u00edtimo|Mar\u00edtimo]] in the [[2016 Ta\u00e7a da Liga Final|Ta\u00e7a da Liga final]], where he also finished as the competition's top goalscorer with four goals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Myson |first=Chris |date=20 May 2016 |title=Benfica romp to Ta\u00e7a da Liga success |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/91/portugal/2016/05/20/23766642/benfica-romp-to-taca-da-liga-success |website=Goal.com |access-date=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nOn 21 July 2016, it was announced that Benfica had purchased the remaining 50% of Jim\u00e9nez's economic rights for \u20ac12&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi/emitentes/docs/FR61071.pdf |title=Comunicado |date=21 July 2016 |website=CMVM |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Announcement |format=PDF |access-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> It was widely reported that this had brought the total value of his transfer to around \u20ac22&nbsp;million, making Jim\u00e9nez the most expensive player in Portuguese football history (this remains unsubstantiated, since the \u20ac9.836&nbsp;million spent by Benfica in 2015 included various costs besides the transfer fee)<ref name=\"Prospeto de oferta p\u00fablica...\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=OFICIAL: Benfica paga mais 12 milh\u00f5es por Jim\u00e9nez |trans-title=Official: Benfica pay another 12 million for Jim\u00e9nez |url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/raul-jimenez/liga/oficial-benfica-paga-mais-12-milhoes-por-jimenez |work=Mais Futebol |language=Portuguese |access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> and the most expensive Mexican player.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rosenblatt |first=Ryan |date=22 July 2016 |title=Raul Jimenez becomes the most expensive Mexican transfer ever |url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/raul-jimenez-mexico-el-tri-benfica-atletico-madrid-transfer-072116 |publisher=Fox Soccer |access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> In that season, he played in the [[2017 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal Final|Ta\u00e7a de Portugal final]], which Benfica won over [[Vitoria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] (2\u20131).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abola.pt/jogodireto/index.aspx?id=251730|title=A Bola - Jogo em direto|website=www.abola.pt}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nJim\u00e9nez came off the bench to score Benfica's final goal in their [[2017 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|3\u20131 Super Cup win over Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]]. On 17 December, Jim\u00e9nez made his 100th appearance for Benfica in all competitions following an away 5\u20131 win over [[C.D. Tondela|Tondela]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez y sus 100 partidos con Benfica |url=https://www.goal.com/es-mx/noticias/raul-jimenez-y-sus-100-partidos-con-benfica/1h4njre6tc2jy1nfvbf3pejg7o |work=Goal |language=Spanish |date=17 December 2017 |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Wolverhampton Wanderers====\nOn 12 June 2018, Benfica loaned out Jim\u00e9nez to newly-promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on a season-long loan for a fee of \u20ac3&nbsp;million, with a buyout clause of \u20ac38&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jimenez completes Molineux move |url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20180612-jimenez-completes-molineux-move/ |date=12 June 2018 |website=Wolverhampton Wanderers}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=12 June 2018|title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez loaned out to Wolverhampton|url=https://www.slbenfica.pt/en-us/agora/noticias/2017_2018/06/12/futebol-benfica-raul-jimenez-emprestado-ao-wolverhampton|work=S.L. Benfica|access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://web3.cmvm.pt/sdi/emitentes/docs/FR68989.pdf |title=Comunicado |date=12 June 2018 |website=CMVM |publisher=S.L. Benfica |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Announcement |format=PDF |access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref> On 29 June, it was reported that he had extended his contract with Benfica until June 2021 before being loaned out.<ref>{{cite news |date=29 June 2018 |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez renovou at\u00e9 2021 antes de ser emprestado ao Wolverhampton |trans-title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez renewed until 2021 before being loaned out to Wolverhampton |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/raul-jimenez-renovou-ate-2021-antes-de-ser-emprestado-ao-wolverhampton |language=pt |work=SAPO Desporto |access-date=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nJim\u00e9nez made his unofficial debut with the team on 22 July in a semifinal match against [[VfL Bochum]] in the H-Hotels Cup, where he failed to convert a penalty, the first following his perfect conversion rate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez missed a penalty in his debut with Wolverhampton, short streak! |url=https://www.archysport.com/raul-jimenez-missed-a-penalty-in-his-debut-with-wolverhampton-short-streak-the-monclova-press/ |website=Archysport.com |date=23 July 2018 |accessdate=15 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016094326/https://www.archysport.com/raul-jimenez-missed-a-penalty-in-his-debut-with-wolverhampton-short-streak-the-monclova-press/ |archive-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 11 August, Jim\u00e9nez marked his competitive debut for Wolves by scoring the equalizing goal that earned the home team a 2\u20132 draw with visiting [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on the opening weekend of the Premier League [[2018\u201319 Premier League|season]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves 2-2 Everton |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45067374 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref> On 16 September, Jim\u00e9nez scored the only goal in the victory over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves 1-0 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45462680 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> On 22 September, he provided an assist to [[Jo\u00e3o Moutinho]] to tie the match 1\u20131 against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the league.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wolves hold struggling Man U to 1-1 in EPL |url=https://apnews.com/956a5d1db20446f8960dc35b54a25394 |work=AP News |date=22 September 2018 |access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref> On 29 September, he provided an assist to [[Ivan Cavaleiro]] to score the first goal in a 2\u20130 victory over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wolves leave it late to beat Southampton and continue hot start |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/wolves-vs-southampton-final-score-match-report-premier-league-epl-goals-video-a8560981.html |work=The Independent |date=29 September 2018 |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref> On 6 October, Jim\u00e9nez provided the assist for [[Matt Doherty (footballer born 1992)|Matt Doherty]]'s goal in his team's 1\u20130 away victory over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]; it was his third assist of the season, meaning Jim\u00e9nez was involved in a goal in each of the previous four league games for Wolves, assisting in the past three after scoring in the game prior to that.<ref>{{cite news |title=Crystal Palace 0-1 Wolves |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45689299 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref> On 11 November, he provided the assist to Ivan Cavaleiro in the 1\u20131 draw against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], taking his season assist tally to four.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nuno proud of Wolves display at Arsenal |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/nuno-espirito-santo-proud-wolves-arsenal-premier-league/ku75mdst8s5f1eco6f2o4o1r0 |work=Goal.com |first=Ryan |last=Benson |date=11 November 2018 |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez scored Wolves' first goal in a 2\u20131 win against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] on 5 December.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves 2\u20131 Chelsea:Ra\u00f9l Jim\u00e9nez & Diogo Jota inspire hosts to victory |work=[[BBC Sport]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46367295 |first=Michael |last=Emons |date=5 December 2018}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez scored the first goal in Wolves's 2\u20130 win over [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on 15 December. This was the first time Wolves had won three consecutive Premier League games and the first time Wolves had won three in a row in the top flight of English football since 1980.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves 2\u20130 Bournemouth |work=[[BBC Sport]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46491856 |first=Rory |last=McAtamney |date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2019, with his goal for Wolves in their 1\u20131 draw against Chelsea, Jim\u00e9nez tied [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] as the Wolves player with the most Premier League goals scored in a single season with twelve.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea 1-1 Wolves |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47431205 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref> Six days later, Jim\u00e9nez scored the first goal for Wolverhampton in a 2\u20131 home victory over Manchester United to advance to the semi-final of the [[2018\u201319 FA Cup|FA Cup]]; it was his third goal in the cup, and fifteenth of the season in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wolves 2-1 Manchester United: Raul Jimenez and Diogo Jota propel Wanderers to Wembley FA Cup semi-final |url=https://talksport.com/football/fa-cup/512653/wolves-2-1-manchester-united-raul-jimenez-diogo-jota/ |website=talkSPORT |accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2019, it was announced that Wolves had exercised their \u20ac38&nbsp;million option to sign Jim\u00e9nez on a four-year contract, with the loan move becoming permanent on 1 July.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jim\u00e9nez becomes permanent Wolves player |url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20190404-jim%C3%A9nez-becomes-permanent-wolves-player/ |website=Wolverhampton Wanderers |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=4 April 2019 |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez transfer formalized |url=https://www.slbenfica.pt/en-us/agora/noticias/2018-2019/04/04/futebol-benfica-comunicado-venda-de-raul-jimenez |work=S.L. Benfica |access-date=7 April 2019}}</ref> The signing was for a reported club-record \u00a330&nbsp;million, surpassing [[Adama Traor\u00e9 (footballer, born 1996)|Adama Traor\u00e9]]'s \u00a318&nbsp;million transfer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez: Wolves sign Benfica striker for club record \u00a330m |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47811338 |website=BBC |access-date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe scored his 13th Premier League goal on 27 April, heading in a [[Diogo Jota]] cross from close range to open the scoring in the 2\u20131 away win against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], becoming the Wolves player with the most goals scored in a single Premier League season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Watford 1-2 Wolves |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47994864 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=27 April 2019}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez scored 17 goals across all competitions, and capped off his season by being voted the Wolves Players' Player of the Season on 15 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/05/14/joao-moutinho-takes-top-prize-at-wolves-awards/|title=Joao Moutinho takes top prize at Wolves awards|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|first=Tim|last=Spiers|date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\n====2019\u201320 season====\nOn 9 July 2019, [[Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo]] excused Jim\u00e9nez from attending the team's pre-season tour in China and as well as possibly the club's Europa League debut in order to rest after the summer activity he had with the Mexico national team.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wolves boss Nuno warns against Raul Jimenez burnout |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/07/09/wolves-boss-nuno-warns-against-raul-jimenez-burnout/ |website=Express & Star |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref> On 1 August, he scored his 50th and 51st goals in Europe after netting a brace against [[Crusaders F.C.|Crusaders]] in the second qualifying round of the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite news|date=1 August 2019|title=Con Wolverhampton, Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez anota su gol 50 en Europa|url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/europa-league/gol-50-raul-jimenez-europa-anota-wolverhampton|work=Medio Tiempo|language=es|access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=1 August 2019|title=RA\u00daL JIM\u00c9NEZ SUPER\u00d3 LOS 50 GOLES EN EUROPA AL ANOTAR DOBLETE VS CRUSADERS|url=http://www.record.com.mx/futbol-futbol-internacional-mexicanos-en-el-extranjero/raul-jimenez-supero-los-50-goles-en-europa-al|work=R\u00e9cord|language=es|access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref> In the third qualifying round, Jim\u00e9nez scored another brace to help Wolves to a 4\u20130 first-leg win over Armenian side [[FC Pyunik]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Poole |first=Harry |title=Pyunik 0-4 Wolves |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49270575/ |website=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2019 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> He scored his first Premier League goal of the season on 25 August in the 1\u20131 draw against Burnley, converting from the penalty spot at the 97th minute.<ref>{{cite web|title=Raul Jim\u00e9nez rescues Wolves with late penalty to deny impressive Burnley |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/aug/25/wolves-burnley-premier-league-match-report |work=The Guardian|first=Paul|last=MacInnes|date=25 August 2019}}</ref> On 2 November, he would score his team's equalizer at the 76th minute in a 1\u20131 result against Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arsenal drop points again after Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez header earns Wolves draw|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/nov/02/arsenal-wolves-premier-league-match-report|work=The Guardian|first=Nick|last=Ames|date=2 November 2019}}</ref> On 28 November, he would score a goal and provided two assists in a 3\u20133 result against Portuguese club [[S.C. Braga|Braga]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wolves player ratings: Raul Jimenez stars as Nuno's side qualify with Braga draw|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/wolves-player-ratings-raul-jimenez-17334458|work=Birminghammail.co.uk|first=Alex|last=Dicken|date=28 November 2019}}</ref> As a result of his November performances, Jim\u00e9nez was voted PFA Player of the Month.<ref name=\"PFA\">{{cite web|title=Jimenez wins PFA Bristol Street Motors Player of the Month|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20191129-jimenez-wins-pfa-bristol-street-motors-player-of-the-month/#:~:targetText=Wolves'%20in%2Dform%20striker%20Raul,second%20with%2014%20per%20cent.|website=Wolves.co.uk|date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 December, Jim\u00e9nez, in scoring Wolves' second goal in their 3\u20132 home win over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], scored his eighth goal in the Premier League and 17th across all competitions, equaling his total from the previous season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jimenez continues stunning Wolves form with starring role against Man City|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/jimenez-continues-stunning-wolves-form-with-starring-role/1vw1ideojh7niz6gh26i2rzks|work=Goal.com|first=Kieran|last=Francis|date=27 December 2019}}</ref> On 18 January, he would score a brace in a 3\u20132 victory over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and became the Wolves all-time scorer in a single Premier League campaign with 15 matches remaining.<ref>{{cite web|title=Raul Jimenez becomes Wolves EPL all-time top scorer|url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/01/18/football/1579373090_680564.html|work=AS|first=Rodrigo|last=Serrano|date=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Mexico U23===\n====2012 Toulon Tournament====\nIn 2012, Jim\u00e9nez was selected by coach [[Luis Fernando Tena]] to participate in [[2012 Toulon Tournament|that year's]] [[Toulon Tournament]] with the [[Mexico national under-23 football team|under-23 side]]. Jim\u00e9nez managed to score Mexico's third goal in the 4\u20132 victory over the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] in the semi-finals on 30 May.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gomez |first=Eric |title=Mexico U23 4-2 Netherlands U23: El Tri, Fabian make Toulon history |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/114/mexico/2012/05/30/3137538/mexico-u23-4-2-netherlands-u23-el-tri-fabian-make-toulon?ICID=AR_RA_2 |publisher=Goal.com |access-date=31 May 2012}}</ref> Mexico would subsequently win the final, defeating [[Turkey A2 national football team|Turkey]] 3\u20130, with Jim\u00e9nez earning a starting berth and playing 65 minutes.<ref name=\"Gomez\">{{cite web |last=Gomez |first=Eric |title=Mexico U23 3-0 Turkey U23: El Tri win their first Toulon tournament |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/114/mexico/2012/06/01/3142505/mexico-u23-3-0-turkey-u23-el-tri-win-their-first-toulon |publisher=Goal.com |access-date=1 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2012 Summer Olympics====\nJim\u00e9nez made the final cut in the squad participating in the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London, England|London]].<ref>[http://miseleccion.mx/noticias/convocatoria-de-la-seleccion-mexicana-para-juegos-olimpicos/ \"Convocatoria de la Selecci\u00f3n Mexicana para Juegos Olimpicos\"]. (In Spanish) ''Mi Seleccion''. Retrieved 20 June 2012.</ref> He made his Olympic debut in the group stage match against [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea]] on 26 July, which ended in a 0\u20130 draw, with Jim\u00e9nez coming in as a substitute and coming close to scoring a late goal, with the ball ricocheting off the goalkeeper's left-hand post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/2012|title=London 2012|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He subsequently made appearances against [[Switzerland national under-23 football team|Switzerland]],<ref>[http://www.london2012.com/football/event/men/match=fbm400b05/index.html?v=20120801-165824816: \"Mexico vs. Switzerland\"]. London 2012. Retrieved 1 August 2012.</ref> [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]],<ref>[http://www.london2012.com/football/event/men/match=fbm400303/index.html: \"Mexico vs. Senegal\"]. London 2012. Retrieved 4 August 2012.</ref> [[Japan national under-23 football team|Japan]],<ref>[http://www.london2012.com/football/event/men/match=fbm400202/index.html: \"Mexico vs. Japan\"]. London 2012. Retrieved 7 August 2012.</ref> and [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil]] in the final, coming on as a substitute in those matches. Mexico would go on to defeat Brazil 2\u20131 and win the gold medal.<ref>[http://www.london2012.com/football/event/men/match=fbm400101/index.html: \"Mexico vs. Brazil\"]. London 2012. Retrieved 11 August 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Borden\">{{cite news |last=Borden |first=Sam |title=Mexico Has Its Moment in Upset Over Brazil |url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2012/08/12/sports/olympics/mexico-downs-brazil-in-olympics-soccer.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=11 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico national team===\nJim\u00e9nez made his debut for the senior national team in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] on 30 January 2013, coming on as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2013/01/31/mexico-and-denmark-play-to-1-1-draw-in-exhibition-match/ |title=Mexico and Denmark play to 1-1 draw in exhibition match |work=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n====2013 FIFA Confederations Cup====\nOn 20 May 2013, Jim\u00e9nez was named in the 23-man squad participating in the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup]] held in Brazil,<ref>{{cite web |title=Convocatoria de la Selecci\u00f3n Mayor |url=http://www.femexfut.org.mx/portalv2/aspx/WEB_DetalleNoticia.aspx?pnIDNtca=40982 |publisher=Femexfut |language=Spanish |access-date=20 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608013603/http://www.femexfut.org.mx/portalv2/aspx/WEB_DetalleNoticia.aspx?pnIDNtca=40982 |archivedate=8 June 2013 }}</ref> and featured in all three group games for a combined 96 minutes. On 22 June, he was named in the starting eleven for the third match against [[Japan national football team|Japan]], being substituted off in the 90th minute for [[Javier Aquino]] in Mexico's 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan 1 Mexico 2: Hernandez heads home twice before shocking late miss as both teams bow out of Confederations Cup |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2346601/Japan-1-Mexico-2-Confederations-Cup--match-report-Javier-Hernandez-scores-twice-misses-penalty.html |newspaper=Daily Mail |access-date=22 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup====\nOn 26 June 2013, it was announced that Jim\u00e9nez was included in Mexico's 23-man squad for the [[2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], replacing midfielder [[David Cabrera Pujol|David Cabrera]] due to injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez jugar\u00e1 la Copa Oro |url=http://www.espn.go.com/deportes/nota?storyId=1835794&src=desktop&cc=3888 |website=ESPN Deportes |language=Spanish |access-date=26 June 2013}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He was a starter and played in every group stage match, managing to score against [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] in Mexico's 2\u20130 win on 11 July.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mayers |first=Joshua |date=11 July 2013 |title=Mexico knocks off Canada, 2\u20130, in Gold Cup match |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/mexico-knocks-off-canada-2-0-in-gold-cup-match/ |newspaper=The Seattle Times |access-date=12 July 2013}}</ref> On 20 July, Jim\u00e9nez scored the only goal in the quarterfinal victory over [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Lee Rigg |first=Zach |date=21 July 2013 |title=Mexico Edged Trinidad & Tobago: Raul Jimenez Goal Lifts El Tri Into Gold Cup Semifinal (VIDEO) |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/21/mexico-gold-cup-trinidad-tobago_n_3630022.html |website=The Huffington Post |access-date=21 July 2013}}</ref> Mexico would be eliminated by [[Panama national football team|Panama]] in the semifinal.\n\n====2014 FIFA World Cup====\nDuring the World Cup qualifier match against [[Panama national football team|Panama]] on 11 October 2013, in which Mexico needed a victory to not complicate the qualification process, Jim\u00e9nez would go on to score a [[bicycle kick]] goal that led to Mexico's 2\u20131 victory;<ref>{{cite web |title=Bicycle kick goal gives Mexico win |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/news/story/_/id/1580882/raul-jimenez-bicycle-kick-gives-mexico-win-panama |work=ESPN |access-date=13 July 2018}}</ref> the goal would go on to win the 2013 edition of [[CONCACAF Awards#Goal of the Year|CONCACAF Goal of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peralta, Morgan named 2013 CONCACAF Players of the Year |url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/peralta-morgan-named-2013-concacaf-players-of-the-year |publisher=CONCACAF.com |accessdate=15 December 2013 |date=13 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214152731/http://www.concacaf.com/article/peralta-morgan-named-2013-concacaf-players-of-the-year |archive-date=14 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 5 June 2014, Jim\u00e9nez was confirmed in coach Miguel Herrera's final 23-man team participating in the 2014 FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mexico squad for 2014 World Cup: the 23 chosen by Miguel Herrera |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/05/mexico-squad-2014-world-cup |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=5 June 2014}}</ref> He did not appear in Mexico's opener against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]]. On 17 June, Jim\u00e9nez made his World Cup debut against host nation [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], entering as a substitute for [[Giovani dos Santos]] in the 84th minute.<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Ben |date=17 June 2014 |title=Brazil 0-0 Mexico |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25285134 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica====\nIn Mexico's second game of the [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] tournament against hosts [[Chile national football team|Chile]], Jim\u00e9nez headed from a corner to give Mexico the 2\u20131 lead in an eventual 3\u20133 draw at the [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos|Estadio Nacional]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hosts Chile draw with Mexico in six-goal Copa Am\u00e9rica thriller |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/16/chile-draw-mexico-copa-america-thriller |access-date=24 June 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Reuters |date=16 June 2015}}</ref> In their next match against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] on 19 June, he scored from the penalty spot after [[Gabriel Achilier]] brought down [[Hugo Ayala]], but the 1\u20132 defeat saw Mexico eliminated in last place in [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|their group]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolanos, Valencia score as Ecuador bounce Mexico from Copa America |url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/copa-america/match/409844/mexico-ecuador/report |access-date=24 June 2015 |publisher=ESPN |date=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario====\nJim\u00e9nez was called up by [[Juan Carlos Osorio]] to participate in the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/mexico-announces-team-for-copa-america-centenario-and-it-looks-scary-good-051716|title=Mexico announces team for Copa America Centenario and it looks scary good|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|date=17 May 2016}}</ref> He made three appearance but did not score.\n\n====2017 FIFA Confederations Cup====\n[[File:2017 Confederation Cup - MEXNZL - Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez.jpg|thumb|upright=1.00|Jim\u00e9nez at the 2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]]\nJim\u00e9nez was included the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]] roster.<ref>{{cite web|title=M\u00e9xico defini\u00f3 a los 23 convocados que ir\u00e1n a la Copa Confederaciones de Rusia|url=https://www.tudn.com/futbol/mexico/mexico-definio-a-los-23-convocados-que-iran-a-la-copa-confederaciones-de-rusia|work=TUDN|language=Spanish|date=8 June 2017}}</ref> He scored his only goal in the tournament against [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] to tie the game 1\u20131; the team would go on winning the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/06/21/mexico-new-zealand-confederations-cup-goals-video-chicharito-vela-dos-santos|title=Watch: Mexico battles back for Confed Cup win vs. NZ|website=SI.com}}</ref>\n\n====2018 FIFA World Cup====\nJim\u00e9nez was named in Mexico's 23-man final squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad - Final 23-man lists - Goal.com|website=www.goal.com}}</ref> He would go on to appear as a substitute in both the first group stage match against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and the round-of-16 match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], but did not score.\n\n====2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup====\nOn 5 June 2019, Jim\u00e9nez was included in the Mexico squad for the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://miseleccion.mx/noticias/2560/Convocatoria-Final-para-Copa-Oro-2019|title=Convocatoria Final para Copa Oro 2019|website=MiSeleccion.mx|publisher=Mexican Football Federation|date=5 June 2019|accessdate=5 June 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref> In the team's debut match against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]], Jim\u00e9nez scored twice in ''El Tri's'' 7-0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calhoun |first=Damian |date=15 June 2019 |title=Galaxy's Uriel Antuna scores a hat trick in Mexico's dominant win over Cuba in Gold Cup |url=https://www.dailynews.com/2019/06/15/galaxys-uriel-antuna-scores-a-hat-trick-in-mexicos-dominant-win-over-cuba-in-gold-cup/ |work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref> He scored his third goal in the 3\u20132 victory over [[Martinique national football team|Martinique]] as Mexico topped Group A and advanced to the knockout round.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Steve |date=23 June 2019 |title=Mexico tops Martinique 3-2 to reach Gold Cup quarterfinals |url=https://www.apnews.com/847c9b6faa2b4fbebf3d22f56e154877 |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref> In the quarter-final match against [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], Jim\u00e9nez scored in the 1\u20131 draw, subsequently missing his penalty in Mexico's 5\u20134 shootout victory.<ref>{{cite news |last=Downie |first=Andrew |date=29 June 2019 |title=Mexico into Gold Cup semis after shootout win over Costa Rica |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-goldcup-mex-cri-report/mexico-into-gold-cup-semis-after-shootout-win-over-costa-rica-idUSKCN1TV05M |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref> In the semi-final match against [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]] on 2 July, Jim\u00e9nez scored the game's only goal via the penalty spot after being fouled in the first half of extra-time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Marshall |first=John |date=3 July 2019 |title=Mexico outlasts Haiti 1-0 in Gold Cup semifinals |url=https://www.apnews.com/3082295909cf4a73b684e5f992504ff2 |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> In the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup Final|final]] against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], Jim\u00e9nez provided a back-heel pass for [[Jonathan dos Santos]]' goal, the only one of the match as Mexico won their eighth Gold Cup.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 July 2019 |title=Mexico beats U.S. men's national soccer team in Concacaf Gold Cup final |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/07/gold-cup-final-mexico-beats-usmnt-jonathan-dos-santos-goal/1670680001/ |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref> He was awarded the Golden Ball Award, playing in all six of Mexico's matches and scoring five goals.<ref name=\"GC Gold Ball\">{{cite web|title=2019 Concacaf Golden Ball |url=https://www.goldcup.org/en/scotiabank/golden-ball-award-presented-by-scotiabank |website= goldcup.org|date=7 July 2019|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 CONCACAF Nations League====\nOn 15 November 2019, Jim\u00e9nez scored a brace and contributed an assist in ''El Tri'''s 3\u20130 victory over Panama.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico ratings: Jimenez 9/10, Alvarez 8/10 in dominant El Tri win|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/mexico/story/3991300/mexico-ratings-jimenez-9-10-alvarez-8-10-in-dominant-el-tri-win?src=com|first=Cesar|last=Hernandez|date=15 November 2019|work=ESPN}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA forward, Jim\u00e9nez is known for his physical presence in the penalty area, as well as his ability to hold-up play and his ability in the air, which allows him to head long passes on or bring the ball down and bring others into play.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez - The Mexican Tank |url=http://www.marca.com/2014/08/15/en/football/spanish_football/1408135890.html |work=Marca |first=Marcos |last=L\u00f3pez |date=15 August 2014 |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref> Despite his size, however, he has been described as not just a \"traditional number nine,\" but a \"well-rounded player.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Raul Jimenez The Expert View |url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/club/20180612-raul-jimenez-the-expert-view/ |work=Wolves.co.uk |date=12 June 2018 |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref> His playing style has led to comparisons with [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Talentos de Exportaci\u00f3n: Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez, el 'Zlatan' de Am\u00e9rica |url=http://www.goal.com/es-mx/news/4851/especiales/2013/04/08/3886246/talentos-de-exportaci%C3%B3n-ra%C3%BAl-jim%C3%A9nez-el-zlatan-de-am%C3%A9rica |work=Goal.com |first=Eric |last=G\u00f3mez |date=8 April 2013 |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez, el Zlatan Ibrahimovic mexicano |url=http://www.goal.com/es/news/4194/editoriales/2014/08/12/5029707/ra%C3%BAl-jim%C3%A9nez-el-zlatan-ibrahimovic-mexicano |work=Goal.com |first=Andr\u00e9s |last=Crona Zurita |date=12 August 2014 |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez: el 'Zlatan mexicano', prensa lusa |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/internacional/noticias/2014/05/14/raul-jimenez-el-zlatan-mexicano-prensa-lusa |work=Medio Tiempo |date=14 May 2014 |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u00bfSon exageradas las comparaciones entre Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez y Zlatan Ibrahimovic? |url=https://www.sdpnoticias.com/deportes/2014/05/15/son-exageradas-las-comparaciones-entre-raul-jimenez-y-zlatan-ibrahimovic?fb_comment_id=757483710962886_757503850960872#f28d62ea895336 |work=SDP Noticias |date=15 May 2014 |access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref> Jim\u00e9nez is also known for his high penalty conversion rate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez, infalible en los tiros penales |url=https://www.goal.com/es/noticias/raul-jimenez-infalible-tiros-penales/m707c6a4k9991un9o54nczort |work=Goal |language=Spanish |date=8 April 2018 |accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez stats |url=http://espnfc.com/player/_/id/167060/ra\u00fal-jim\u00e9nez?cc=5901 |publisher=[[ESPN FC]]}}</ref><ref>{{ForaDeJogo|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ra\u00fal Jim\u00e9nez |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/raul-alonso-jimenez-rodriguez/209521/ |work=Soccerway |accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental<sup>2</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\" valign=\"center\"|[[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico season|2011\u201312]]\n|[[Liga MX|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|18||2||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||18||2\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Liga MX season|2012\u201313]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Liga MX]]\n|39||14||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||41||14\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Liga MX season|2013\u201314]]\n|35||16||2||1||2||2||39||19\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Liga MX season|2014\u201315]]\n|4||4||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0||4||4\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!96!!36!!4!!1!!2!!2!!102!!39\n|-\n| valign=\"center\" |[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2014\u201315]]\n|[[La Liga]]\n|21||1||5||0||1||0||27||1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" valign=\"center\" |[[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n|[[2015\u201316 S.L. Benfica season|2015\u201316]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Primeira Liga]]\n|28||5||7||4||10||3||45||12\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 S.L. Benfica season|2016\u201317]]\n|19||7||7||3||6||1||32||11\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 S.L. Benfica season|2017\u201318]]\n|33||6||5||2||5||0||43||8\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!80!!18!!24!!9!!22!!4!!147!!32\n|-\n| valign=\"center\" |[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] (loan)\n|[[2018\u201319 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2018\u201319]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"  |[[Premier League]]\n|38||13||6||4||colspan=2|\u2014||44||17\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"center\" |[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2019\u201320]]\n|29||13||2||0||13||9<sup>3</sup>||44||22\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!67!!26!!8!!4!!13!!9!!88!!39\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |Career total\n!263!!80!!36!!14!!37!!15!!337!!110\n|}\n<sup>1</sup>Includes the [[Copa MX]], [[Copa del Rey]], [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]], [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]], [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]] and [[FA Cup]].<br /><sup>2</sup>Includes the [[CONCACAF Champions League]], [[UEFA Champions League]], and the [[UEFA Europa League]].<br /><sup>3</sup>Includes 6 goals scored in UEFA Europa League qualifying rounds.\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 19 November 2019}}<ref>{{NFT player|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=6 | [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| 2013||20||4\n|-\n| 2014||8||2\n|-\n| 2015||14||3\n|-\n| 2016||7||1\n|-\n| 2017||12||4\n|-\n| 2018||9||2\n|-\n| 2019||12||8\n|-\n! Total||81||24\n|}\n\n====International goals====\n:''Scores and results list Mexico's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Goal!!Date!!Venue!!Opponent!!Score!!Result!!Competition\n|-\n| align=center| 1. || 11 July 2013 || [[CenturyLink Field]], [[Seattle]], United States || {{fb|CAN}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 || rowspan=2 | [[2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup Group A|2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|-\n| align=center| 2. || 20 July 2013 || [[Georgia Dome]], [[Atlanta]], United States || {{fb|TRI}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 1\u20130\n|-\n| align=center| 3. || 11 October 2013 || rowspan=2 | [[Estadio Azteca]], [[Mexico City]], Mexico || {{fb|PAN}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20131 || align=center | 2\u20131 || rowspan=2 | [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round|2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| align=center| 4. || 13 November 2013 || {{fb|NZL}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center |5\u20131\n|-\n| align=center| 5. || rowspan=2 | 18 November 2014 || rowspan=2 | [[Borisov Arena]], [[Barysaw|Borisov]], Belarus || rowspan=2 | {{fb|BLR}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || rowspan=2 align=center | 2\u20133 || rowspan=2 | [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n| align=center| 6 || align=center | '''2'''\u20131\n|-\n| align=center| 7. || 15 June 2015 || [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos|Estadio Nacional]], [[Santiago]], Chile || {{fb|CHI}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20131 || align=center | 3\u20133 || rowspan=2|[[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]]\n|-\n| align=center| 8. || 19 June 2015 || [[Estadio El Teniente]], [[Rancagua]], Chile || {{fb|ECU}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20132 || align=center | 1\u20132\n|-\n| align=center| 9. || 4 September 2015 || [[Rio Tinto Stadium]], [[Sandy, Utah|Sandy]], United States || {{fb|TRI}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20132 || align=center | 3\u20133 || Friendly\n|-\n| align=center| 10. || 2 September 2016 || [[Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n]], [[San Salvador]], El Salvador || {{fb|SLV}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20131 || align=center | 3\u20131 || [[