{"title_page": "Tom\u00e1\u0161 Fleischmann", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| alt = \n| image = Tomas Fleischmann 2012-03-09.JPG\n| caption = \n| image_size = 230px\n| played_for = [[Washington Capitals]]<br>[[Colorado Avalanche]]<br>[[Florida Panthers]]<br>[[Anaheim Ducks]]<br>[[Montreal Canadiens]]<br>[[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| ntl_team = Czech Republic\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left Wing]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb = 192\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|5|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Kop\u0159ivnice]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| draft = 63rd overall\n| draft_year = 2002\n| draft_team = [[Detroit Red Wings]]\n| career_start = 2004\n| career_end = 2016\n}}\n'''Tom\u00e1\u0161 Fleischmann''' (born May 16, 1984) is a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|winger]]. He most notably played in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).\n\n== Playing career ==\nFleischmann originally played three years in his native Czech Republic as a junior with [[HC V\u00edtkovice Steel|HC Vitkovic]], playing at both the under-18 and under-20 levels. As a prolific scorer, Fleischmann experienced his first taste of professional hockey late in the 2002\u201303 season, appearing in eight games out on loan with third-division team HC [[Nov\u00fd Ji\u010d\u00edn]].\n\nFleischmann was subsequently drafted in the second round, 63rd overall, by the [[Detroit Red Wings]] in the [[2002 NHL Entry Draft]]. With aspirations for an NHL career, Fleischmann immediately made the transition to North America by joining the [[Moose Jaw Warriors]] of the [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL) for the [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303 season]]. In his first season, Fleischmann emerged as a leader on the offence for the Warriors, finishing with 71 points in 65 games. Helping Moose Jaw reach the second round of the post-season, he led the team with 11 assists and 15 points in 12 games.\n\nIn the [[2003\u201304 WHL season|2003\u201304 season]], Fleischmann improved his offensive numbers with Moose Jaw to post 30 goals and 75 points in 60 games and earn selection to the WHL East Second All-Star Team. During the campaign, on February 27, 2004, Fleischmann's NHL rights were traded with draft picks by the Red Wings to the [[Washington Capitals]] in exchange for fellow countryman [[Robert Lang (ice hockey)|Robert Lang]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Wings acquire Lang from Capitals|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/2004-02-27-wings-caps-lang_x.htm|newspaper= [[USA Today]] | first=Joseph | last=White | date= 2004-02-28 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tomas Fleischmann14.jpg|thumb|Fleischmann as a member of the Capitals.]]\nOn June 1, 2006, Fleischmann was signed by the Capitals to a three-year, entry level contract. In his first full professional season, he was assigned to their [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Portland Pirates]], for the duration of the [[2004\u201305 AHL season|2004\u201305 season]] and contributed within a limited role with a modest 19 points in 53 games.\n\nIn the following season, [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]], Fleischmann started the year in the AHL with the Capitals' new affiliate, the [[Hershey Bears]]. Scoring 13 points in his first 10 games of the year, he received his first recall to the Capitals on November 3, 2005.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=462022 | title = Capitals recall Tomas Fleischmann and Nolan Yonkman | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2005-11-03 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref> He then made his NHL debut the same day, appearing for Washington in an 8\u20131 defeat against the [[Philadelphia Flyers]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20051103_WAS@PHI | title = Flyers continue home dominance against Capitals | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2005-11-03 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref> In his third game with the Capitals, he collected his first NHL point, an assist on a goal to [[Brian Willsie]], in a 5\u20134 victory over the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] on November 6.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20051106_TOR@WAS | title = Capitals edge Maple Leafs on Ovechkins' two goal outing | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2005-11-06 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref> Despite a near month-long stay, he was returned to Hershey and under the tutelage of Head Coach [[Bruce Boudreau]], progressed to lead the team with 30 goals in just 57 games. In the [[Calder Cup]] playoffs, Fleischmann helped carry the Bears to the Championship, leading the League with 21 assists and the team with 32 points in 20 games.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://voices.washingtonpost.com/capitalsinsider/bruce-boudreau/hannan-makes-his-practice-debu.html | title = Scott Hannan makes his practice debut for Capitals | newspaper = [[Washington Post]] | date = 2010-12-01 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\nFleischmann failed to make the Capitals' opening night roster out of training camp for the [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307 season]] and scored 51 points in only 45 games in spending the majority of the first half of the campaign with the Bears. On February 24, 2007, Fleishmann scored his first NHL goal in a 4\u20132 victory against [[Martin Brodeur]] and the [[New Jersey Devils]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://sports.yahoo.com/nhl/recap?gid=2007022411 | title = Capitals 4, Devils 2 | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date = 2007-02-27 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> He remained in Washington to play in the team's final 21 games and on March 18, 2007, he recorded the first multi-point game of his career, scoring the first two goals of the game and assisting in two others to be named second star of the game in a 7\u20131 rout of the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20070318_TB@WAS | title = Semin's natural hat-trick in second highlights blowout of Lightning | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2007-03-18| accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> In returning to the AHL to help the Bears defend the Calder Cup, Fleischmann again led the team in the playoff scoring with 21 points in 19 games. Although suffering defeat in the finals to the [[Hamilton Bulldogs (AHL)|Hamilton Bulldogs]], for the second consecutive post-season he led the AHL in assists, with 16.\n\nPrior to the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 season]], Fleischmann was re-signed by the Capitals to a one-year contract on October 1, 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=372752 | title = Around the NHL | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2007-10-01 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> Re-united with Bruce Boudreau early into his first full season in the NHL, he established a role as a skilled utility player within the Capitals and was re-signed to a two-year extension during the season on February 13, 2008.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=462685 | title = Capitals re-sign Left Wing Tomas Fleischmann to two-year contract | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2008-02-13 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> He finished to score 10 goals and 30 points in 75 games as the Capitals qualified for the [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] for the first time in four seasons. Fleischmann made his post-season debut against the opening game against Philadelphia Flyers on April 11, 2008, but played in only two games in the Capitals' eventual Game 7 defeat in the Quarter-finals to the Flyers.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/recap.htm?id=2007030131 | title = Capitals 5, Flyers 4 | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2008-04-11 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\nFleischmann backed-up the play of his previous season, appearing in 73 games and improving to score 19 goals and 37 points for the Capitals in [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]. He scored his first playoff goal in the opening game of the Quarter-finals, a 4\u20133 defeat to the [[New York Rangers]], on April 15, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20090415_NYR@WAS | title = Rangers open series against Capitals with tough road win | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2009-04-15 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> Appearing in all 14 playoff games for Washington, he recorded three goals and one assist.\n\nAfter returning to the Czech Republic in the off-season, Fleischmann was found to have developed a blood clot in his leg due to [[deep vein thrombosis]] from the cross-Atlantic flight and would miss the pre-season and the start of the [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2009\u201310 season]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/09/13/AR2009091302369.html | title = Capitals' Tomas Fleischmann has blood clot, Michael Nylander plans on staying | newspaper = [[Washington Post]] | date = 2009-09-13 | accessdate = 2010-12-14 | first=Tarik | last=El-Bashir}}</ref> With an initial two-game stint with the Hershey Bears on a conditioning assignment, Fleischmann returned to the Capitals having missed the first 10 games.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=503339 | title = Washington assigns Tomas Fleischmann to Hershey for conditioning stint | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2009-10-24 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> In a break-out season with the [[Presidents' Trophy]]-winning Capitals, Fleischmann posted a career-high 23 goals and 51 points in 69 games. Fleischmann, however, suffered a disappointing post-season, contributing only one assist in six games and was scratched for the deciding game of the series in a shock loss to the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=527428 | title = Capitals dress Scott Walker, scratch Fleischmann | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2010-04-28 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2010, Fleischmann was re-signed as a restricted free agent to a one-year contract with the Capitals.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=535038 | title = Caps sign forward Tomas Fleischmann | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2010-07-27 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> Shifted to [[center (ice hockey)|centre]] by Washington to start the [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311 season]], Fleischmann failed to establish an offensive presence and was demoted as a depth player.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://voices.washingtonpost.com/capitalsinsider/buffalo-sabres/boudreau-it-is-fleischmanns-tu.html | first = Katy | last = Carrera | title = Boudreau: It is Fleischmann's 'turn to sit' | newspaper = [[Washington Post]] | date = 2010-11-17 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> On November 30, 2010, he was traded by the Capitals to the [[Colorado Avalanche]] in exchange for defenceman [[Scott Hannan]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_16742525?IADID | title = Avalanche trade Scott Hannan to Capitals for Tomas Fleischmann | newspaper = [[Denver Post]] | date = 2010-11-30 | accessdate = 2010-12-15 | first1=Adrian | last1=Dater | first2=Mike | last2=Chambers}}</ref> Returning to the left wing position, he made his Avalanche debut in a 2\u20131 overtime defeat to the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] on December 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://sports.yahoo.com/nhl/recap?gid=2010120307 | title = Sutter scores in OT to give Hurricanes 2-1 win | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date = 2010-12-03 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> In his fourth game, his scored his first goal with Colorado in a 4\u20132 victory over the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] on December 10, 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_16826290 | title = Avs' snap skid with win in Atlanta, but Hejduk is injured | newspaper = [[Denver Post]] | date = 2010-12-10 | accessdate = 2010-11-15 | first=Adrian | last=Dater}}</ref> Five days later, Fleischmann notched his first career NHL [[hat-trick]] in a 4\u20133 win over the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].<ref>{{cite web| url =http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=345700| title =Fleischmann's Hat-Trick Carries Avs to Win Over Blackhawks| publisher = [[The Sports Network|TSN]] | date = 2010-12-16 | accessdate = 2010-12-16}}</ref> Fleischmann's torrid start with the Avalanche, scoring 21 points in 22 games, came to a sudden halt on January 20, when it was revealed that he was diagnosed with [[pulmonary emboli]] and would miss the remainder of the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.truehockey.com/articles/Fleischmann-Sees-Specialist-in-DC | title = Fleischmann see specialist in D.C. | website = truehockey.com | date = 2011-03-07 | accessdate = 2011-06-20 | last = Strickland | first = Andy}}</ref>\n\nFleischmann signed a four-year contract worth $18 million with the [[Florida Panthers]] on July 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL Free Agent Tracker|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/feature/?id=25880|work=The Sports Network|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the final year of his contract with the Panthers in the [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315 season]], and with his offensive production having declined each season with Florida, Fleischmann was traded to the [[Anaheim Ducks]] in exchange for [[Dany Heatley]] and a [[2015 NHL Entry Draft|2015]] third-round draft pick on February 28, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=755657 | title = Panthers trade Fleischmann to Ducks for Heatley, Pick | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2015-02-28 | accessdate = 2015-03-01}}</ref> Fleischmann played a complementary role within the Ducks organization, finishing the regular season with 6 points in 14 games. In the post-season, Fleischmann was relegated to a depth role and healthy scratch in appearing only 6 post-season games with the Conference finalist Ducks.\n\nAs an unsigned free agent in the offseason, on September 12, 2015, Fleischmann accepted an invitation to a professional tryout contract with the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=778831 | title = Canadiens invite Fleischmann to camp on tryout | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2015-09-12 | accessdate = 2015-09-12}}</ref>  On October 4, 2015, the Canadiens signed Fleischmann to a one-year,  $750,000 contract. In the [[2015-16 NHL season|2015\u201316]] season, Fleischmann contributed to the Canadiens' early unbeaten success, regaining his offensive presence while featuring on the third line. Fleischmann compiled 10 goals and 10 assists in 57 games with the Canadiens before he was traded to the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] along with teammate [[Dale Weise]] in exchange for a 2018 second-round draft pick and [[Phillip Danault]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/canadiens-trade-weise-fleischmann-to-blackhawks-for-danault-and-a-pick/ | title = Canadiens trade Weise, Fleischmann to Blackhawks for Danault and a pick | publisher = [[Sportsnet.ca]] | date = 2016-02-26 | accessdate = 2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Fleischmann was signed by the [[Minnesota Wild]] to a professional tryout contract. Unfortunately, on September 25, 2016, he was released from by the Wild after failing his physical. With his history of blood clots, the Wild did not disclose the injury out of respect for Fleischmann's privacy.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.twincities.com/2016/09/23/wild-tomas-fleischmann-fails-physical/ | title = Tomas Fleischmann fails physical | publisher = [[TwinCities.com]] | date = 2016-09-23 | accessdate = 2016-09-23}}</ref> Fleischmann later returned to the Florida area with his family and unofficially began his postplaying career by tentatively coaching at the [[Florida Panthers]] youth hockey clinics throughout the [[2016-17 NHL season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref>{{cite web| url =  https://www.nhl.com/panthers/news/fleischmann-finds-joy-in-panthers-hockey-clinics/c-286827496 | title = Fleischmann finds joy in Panthers Hockey Clinics | publisher = [[Florida Panthers]] | date = 2017-02-17 | accessdate = 2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==International play==\n{{MedalTableTop| name = no}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ih|CZE}} }}\n{{MedalSport | [[Ice hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IIHF World U18 Championships|IIHF U18 Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2002 IIHF World U18 Championships|2002 Pie\u0161\u0165any]] | }}\n{{MedalBottom\n}}\nFleischmann first represented the [[Czech Republic men's national ice hockey team|Czech Republic]] during his final junior year in the Czech Republic when he was named to the [[2002 IIHF World U18 Championships|2002]] World Under 18 Championship squad. In eight games in Slovakia, Fleischmann scored one goal and two assists as the Czech Republic defeated [[Finland men's national ice hockey team|Finland]] 4\u20132 to capture the bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/0102/W18/gs/pg000057.htm | title = Czech Rep team statistics | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref>\n\nWhile with the Moose Jaw Warriors, Fleischmann earned consecutive selections in the Czech [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championship]] squad's for [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2003]] and [[2004 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2004]] respective sixth and fourth-place finishes.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.iihf.com/Hydra/Tournaments/output/W20/hydra.iihf.com/data/iihf/output/xml/6/IHM0060CZE_33_11_0.pdf | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15 | title = Czech Republic Team Roster }}</ref> In 13 combined games, Fleischmann posted four goals and two assists.\n\nAfter completing his first professional season with the Capitals in 2007\u201308, Fleischmann was added to his first senior Czech squad at the [[2008 IIHF World Championship|2008]] World Championships in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.iihf.com/channels/iihf-world-championship/teams/cze.html | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15 | title = 2008 Czech World Championship roster }}</ref> Fleischmann scored his first senior goal in a 5\u20130 shutout round-robin win over [[Switzerland men's national ice hockey team|Switzerland]] on May 8, 2008.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/132/IHM132E27_74_3_0.pdf | title =CZE 5, SUI 0 | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2008-05-08 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref> He completed the tournament with five points in seven games as the Czechs finished in fifth place.\n\nAs a part of the Capitals' highest scoring team in 2009\u201310, Fleischmann was selected mid-season to the Czech team for the [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2010 Winter Olympics]] on December 30, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=511663 | title = Tomas Fleischmann named to Czech Republic's Olympic Team | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] |date = 2009-12-30 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref> Fleischmann scored three points in five games for the Czech Republic en route to a disappointing seventh-place finish.\n\n== Career statistics ==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season]] \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]] \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! [[Season (sports)|Season]] \n! Team \n! League \n! GP \n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] \n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] \n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] \n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]] \n! GP \n! G \n! A \n! Pts \n! PIM \n|- \n| 2000\u201301\n| [[HC V\u00edtkovice]]\n| CZE U20\n| 21\n| 4\n| 9\n| 13\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2001\u201302\n| HC V\u00edtkovice\n| CZE U20\n| 44\n| 25\n| 25\n| 50\n| 16\n| 2\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| 2001\u201302\n| HC Nov\u00fd Ji\u010d\u00edn\n| [[2nd Czech Republic Hockey League|CZE.3]]\n| 8\n| 3\n| 2\n| 5\n| 8\n| 7\n| 3\n| 4\n| 7\n| 35\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| [[Moose Jaw Warriors]]\n| [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n| 65\n| 21\n| 50\n| 71\n| 36\n| 12\n| 4\n| 11\n| 15\n| 6\n|-  \n| [[2003\u201304 WHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| Moose Jaw Warriors\n| WHL\n| 60\n| 33\n| 42\n| 75\n| 32\n| 10\n| 3\n| 4\n| 7\n| 10\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2004\u201305 AHL season|2004\u201305]]\n| [[Portland Pirates]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 53\n| 7\n| 12\n| 19\n| 14\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Hershey Bears]]\n| AHL\n| 57\n| 30\n| 33\n| 63\n| 32\n| 20\n| 11\n| 21\n| 32\n| 15\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Washington Capitals]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 14\n| 0\n| 2\n| 2\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2006\u201307 AHL season|2006\u201307]]\n| Hershey Bears\n| AHL\n| 45\n| 22\n| 29\n| 51\n| 22\n| 19\n| 5\n| 16\n| 21\n| 10\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307]]\n| Washington Capitals\n| NHL\n| 29\n| 4\n| 4\n| 8\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308]]\n| Washington Capitals\n| NHL\n| 75\n| 10\n| 20\n| 30\n| 18\n| 2\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]\n| Washington Capitals\n| NHL\n| 73\n| 19\n| 18\n| 37\n| 20\n| 14\n| 3\n| 1\n| 4\n| 4\n|-  \n| [[2009\u201310 AHL season|2009\u201310]]\n| Hershey Bears\n| AHL\n| 2\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2009\u201310]]\n| Washington Capitals\n| NHL\n| 69\n| 23\n| 28\n| 51\n| 28\n| 6\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 6\n|-  \n| [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| Washington Capitals\n| NHL\n| 23\n| 4\n| 6\n| 10\n| 10\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2010\u201311\n| [[Colorado Avalanche]]\n| NHL\n| 22\n| 8\n| 13\n| 21\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2011\u201312 NHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| [[Florida Panthers]]\n| NHL\n| 82\n| 27\n| 34\n| 61\n| 26\n| 7\n| 1\n| 2\n| 3\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2012\u201313 NHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Florida Panthers\n| NHL\n| 48\n| 12\n| 23\n| 35\n| 16\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| Florida Panthers\n| NHL\n| 80\n| 8\n| 20\n| 28\n| 22\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| Florida Panthers\n| NHL\n| 52\n| 7\n| 14\n| 21\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| 2014\u201315\n| [[Anaheim Ducks]]\n| NHL\n| 14\n| 1\n| 5\n| 6\n| 4\n| 6\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2015\u201316 NHL season|2015\u201316]]\n| [[Montr\u00e9al Canadiens]]\n| NHL\n| 57\n| 10\n| 10\n| 20\n| 28\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| 2015\u201316\n| [[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| NHL\n| 19\n| 4\n| 1\n| 5\n| 4\n| 4\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | NHL totals\n! 657\n! 137\n! 198\n! 335\n! 200\n! 39\n! 4\n! 5\n! 9\n! 12\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" ID=\"Table3\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40em\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! Year\n! Team\n! Event\n! Result\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| [[2002 IIHF World U18 Championships|2002]]\n| [[Czech Republic men's national under-18 ice hockey team|Czech Republic]]\n| [[IIHF World U18 Championships|WJC18]]\n| {{brca}}\n| 8\n| 1\n| 2\n| 3\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2003]]\n| [[Czech Republic men's national junior ice hockey team|Czech Republic]]\n| [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|WJC]]\n| 6th\n| 6\n| 2\n| 0\n| 2\n| 0\n|- \n| [[2004 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2004]]\n| Czech Republic\n| WJC\n| 4th\n| 7\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2008 IIHF World Championship|2008]]\n| [[Czech Republic men's national ice hockey team|Czech Republic]]\n| [[IIHF World Championship|WC]]\n| 5th\n| 7\n| 2\n| 3\n| 5\n| 0\n|- \n| [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2010]]\n| Czech Republic\n| [[Ice hockey at the Olympic Games|OG]]\n| 7th\n| 5\n| 1\n| 2\n| 3\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2013 IIHF World Championship|2013]]\n| Czech Republic\n| WC\n| 7th\n| 8\n| 2\n| 0\n| 2\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=4 | Junior totals\n! 21\n! 5\n! 4\n! 9\n! 4\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=4 | Senior totals\n! 20\n! 5\n! 5\n! 10\n! 2\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award\n! Year\n!\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n|-\n| East Second All-Star Team\n| [[2003\u201304 WHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| <ref name = \"Award\">{{cite web| url = http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=3081 | title = Tomas Fleischmann - player profile | publisher = [[The Sports Network]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Tom\u00e1\u0161 Fleischmann}}\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleischmann, Tomas}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anaheim Ducks players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Blackhawks players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Avalanche players]]\n[[Category:Czech expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Czech ice hockey left wingers]]\n[[Category:Detroit Red Wings draft picks]]\n[[Category:Florida Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Hershey Bears players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey players at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Montreal Canadiens players]]\n[[Category:Moose Jaw Warriors players]]\n[[Category:Olympic ice hockey players of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:People from Kop\u0159ivnice]]\n[[Category:Portland Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| alt = \n| image = Tomas Fleischmann 2012-03-09.JPG\n| caption = \n| image_size = 230px\n| played_for = [[Washington Capitals]]<br>[[Colorado Avalanche]]<br>[[Florida Panthers]]<br>[[Anaheim Ducks]]<br>[[Montreal Canadiens]]<br>[[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| ntl_team = Czech Republic\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left Wing]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb = 192\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|5|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Kop\u0159ivnice]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| draft = 63rd overall\n| draft_year = 2002\n| draft_team = [[Detroit Red Wings]]\n| career_start = 2004\n| career_end = 2016\n}}\n'''Tom\u00e1\u0161 Fleischmann''' (born May 16, 1984) is a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|winger]]. He most notably played in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).\n\n== Playing career ==\nFleischmann originally played three years in his native Czech Republic as a junior with [[HC V\u00edtkovice Steel|HC Vitkovic]], playing at both the under-18 and under-20 levels. As a prolific scorer, Fleischmann experienced his first taste of professional hockey late in the 2002\u201303 season, appearing in eight games out on loan with third-division team HC [[Nov\u00fd Ji\u010d\u00edn]].\n\nFleischmann was subsequently drafted in the second round, 63rd overall, by the [[Detroit Red Wings]] in the [[2002 NHL Entry Draft]]. With aspirations for an NHL career, Fleischmann immediately made the transition to North America by joining the [[Moose Jaw Warriors]] of the [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL) for the [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303 season]]. In his first season, Fleischmann emerged as a leader on the offence for the Warriors, finishing with 71 points in 65 games. Helping Moose Jaw reach the second round of the post-season, he led the team with 11 assists and 15 points in 12 games.\n\nIn the [[2003\u201304 WHL season|2003\u201304 season]], Fleischmann improved his offensive numbers with Moose Jaw to post 30 goals and 75 points in 60 games and earn selection to the WHL East Second All-Star Team. During the campaign, on February 27, 2004, Fleischmann's NHL rights were traded with draft picks by the Red Wings to the [[Washington Capitals]] in exchange for fellow countryman [[Robert Lang (ice hockey)|Robert Lang]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Wings acquire Lang from Capitals|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/2004-02-27-wings-caps-lang_x.htm|newspaper= [[USA Today]] | first=Joseph | last=White | date= 2004-02-28 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tomas Fleischmann14.jpg|thumb|Fleischmann as a member of the Capitals.]]\nOn June 1, 2006, Fleischmann was signed by the Capitals to a three-year, entry level contract. In his first full professional season, he was assigned to their [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Portland Pirates]], for the duration of the [[2004\u201305 AHL season|2004\u201305 season]] and contributed within a limited role with a modest 19 points in 53 games.\n\nIn the following season, [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]], Fleischmann started the year in the AHL with the Capitals' new affiliate, the [[Hershey Bears]]. Scoring 13 points in his first 10 games of the year, he received his first recall to the Capitals on November 3, 2005.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=462022 | title = Capitals recall Tomas Fleischmann and Nolan Yonkman | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2005-11-03 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref> He then made his NHL debut the same day, appearing for Washington in an 8\u20131 defeat against the [[Philadelphia Flyers]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20051103_WAS@PHI | title = Flyers continue home dominance against Capitals | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2005-11-03 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref> In his third game with the Capitals, he collected his first NHL point, an assist on a goal to [[Brian Willsie]], in a 5\u20134 victory over the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] on November 6.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20051106_TOR@WAS | title = Capitals edge Maple Leafs on Ovechkins' two goal outing | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2005-11-06 | accessdate = 2010-12-14}}</ref> Despite a near month-long stay, he was returned to Hershey and under the tutelage of Head Coach [[Bruce Boudreau]], progressed to lead the team with 30 goals in just 57 games. In the [[Calder Cup]] playoffs, Fleischmann helped carry the Bears to the Championship, leading the League with 21 assists and the team with 32 points in 20 games.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://voices.washingtonpost.com/capitalsinsider/bruce-boudreau/hannan-makes-his-practice-debu.html | title = Scott Hannan makes his practice debut for Capitals | newspaper = [[Washington Post]] | date = 2010-12-01 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\nFleischmann failed to make the Capitals' opening night roster out of training camp for the [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307 season]] and scored 51 points in only 45 games in spending the majority of the first half of the campaign with the Bears. On February 24, 2007, Fleishmann scored his first NHL goal in a 4\u20132 victory against [[Martin Brodeur]] and the [[New Jersey Devils]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://sports.yahoo.com/nhl/recap?gid=2007022411 | title = Capitals 4, Devils 2 | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date = 2007-02-27 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> He remained in Washington to play in the team's final 21 games and on March 18, 2007, he recorded the first multi-point game of his career, scoring the first two goals of the game and assisting in two others to be named second star of the game in a 7\u20131 rout of the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20070318_TB@WAS | title = Semin's natural hat-trick in second highlights blowout of Lightning | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2007-03-18| accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> In returning to the AHL to help the Bears defend the Calder Cup, Fleischmann again led the team in the playoff scoring with 21 points in 19 games. Although suffering defeat in the finals to the [[Hamilton Bulldogs (AHL)|Hamilton Bulldogs]], for the second consecutive post-season he led the AHL in assists, with 16.\n\nPrior to the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 season]], Fleischmann was re-signed by the Capitals to a one-year contract on October 1, 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=372752 | title = Around the NHL | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2007-10-01 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> Re-united with Bruce Boudreau early into his first full season in the NHL, he established a role as a skilled utility player within the Capitals and was re-signed to a two-year extension during the season on February 13, 2008.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=462685 | title = Capitals re-sign Left Wing Tomas Fleischmann to two-year contract | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2008-02-13 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> He finished to score 10 goals and 30 points in 75 games as the Capitals qualified for the [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] for the first time in four seasons. Fleischmann made his post-season debut against the opening game against Philadelphia Flyers on April 11, 2008, but played in only two games in the Capitals' eventual Game 7 defeat in the Quarter-finals to the Flyers.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/recap.htm?id=2007030131 | title = Capitals 5, Flyers 4 | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2008-04-11 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\nFleischmann backed-up the play of his previous season, appearing in 73 games and improving to score 19 goals and 37 points for the Capitals in [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]. He scored his first playoff goal in the opening game of the Quarter-finals, a 4\u20133 defeat to the [[New York Rangers]], on April 15, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20090415_NYR@WAS | title = Rangers open series against Capitals with tough road win | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = 2009-04-15 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> Appearing in all 14 playoff games for Washington, he recorded three goals and one assist.\n\nAfter returning to the Czech Republic in the off-season, Fleischmann was found to have developed a blood clot in his leg due to [[deep vein thrombosis]] from the cross-Atlantic flight and would miss the pre-season and the start of the [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2009\u201310 season]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/09/13/AR2009091302369.html | title = Capitals' Tomas Fleischmann has blood clot, Michael Nylander plans on staying | newspaper = [[Washington Post]] | date = 2009-09-13 | accessdate = 2010-12-14 | first=Tarik | last=El-Bashir}}</ref> With an initial two-game stint with the Hershey Bears on a conditioning assignment, Fleischmann returned to the Capitals having missed the first 10 games.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=503339 | title = Washington assigns Tomas Fleischmann to Hershey for conditioning stint | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2009-10-24 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> In a break-out season with the [[Presidents' Trophy]]-winning Capitals, Fleischmann posted a career-high 23 goals and 51 points in 69 games. Fleischmann, however, suffered a disappointing post-season, contributing only one assist in six games and was scratched for the deciding game of the series in a shock loss to the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=527428 | title = Capitals dress Scott Walker, scratch Fleischmann | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2010-04-28 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2010, Fleischmann was re-signed as a restricted free agent to a one-year contract with the Capitals.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=535038 | title = Caps sign forward Tomas Fleischmann | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = 2010-07-27 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> Shifted to [[center (ice hockey)|centre]] by Washington to start the [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311 season]], Fleischmann failed to establish an offensive presence and was demoted as a depth player.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://voices.washingtonpost.com/capitalsinsider/buffalo-sabres/boudreau-it-is-fleischmanns-tu.html | first = Katy | last = Carrera | title = Boudreau: It is Fleischmann's 'turn to sit' | newspaper = [[Washington Post]] | date = 2010-11-17 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> On November 30, 2010, he was traded by the Capitals to the [[Colorado Avalanche]] in exchange for defenceman [[Scott Hannan]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_16742525?IADID | title = Avalanche trade Scott Hannan to Capitals for Tomas Fleischmann | newspaper = [[Denver Post]] | date = 2010-11-30 | accessdate = 2010-12-15 | first1=Adrian | last1=Dater | first2=Mike | last2=Chambers}}</ref> Returning to the left wing position, he made his Avalanche debut in a 2\u20131 overtime defeat to the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] on December 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://sports.yahoo.com/nhl/recap?gid=2010120307 | title = Sutter scores in OT to give Hurricanes 2-1 win | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date = 2010-12-03 | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref> In his fourth game, his scored his first goal with Colorado in a 4\u20132 victory over the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] on December 10, 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_16826290 | title = Avs' snap skid with win in Atlanta, but Hejduk is injured | newspaper = [[Denver Post]] | date = 2010-12-10 | accessdate = 2010-11-15 | first=Adrian | last=Dater}}</ref> Five days later, Fleischmann notched his first career NHL [[hat-trick]] in a 4\u20133 win over the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].<ref>{{cite web| url =http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=345700| title =Fleischmann's Hat-Trick Carries Avs to Win Over Blackhawks| publisher = [[The Sports Network|TSN]] | date = 2010-12-16 | accessdate = 2010-12-16}}</ref> Fleischmann's torrid start with the Avalanche, scoring 21 points in 22 games, came to a sudden halt on January 20, when it was revealed that he was diagnosed with [[pulmonary emboli]] and would miss the remainder of the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.truehockey.com/articles/Fleischmann-Sees-Specialist-in-DC | title = Fleischmann see specialist in D.C. | website = truehockey.com | date = 2011-03-07 | accessdate = 2011-06-20 | last = Strickland | first = Andy}}</ref>\n\nFleischmann signed a four-year contract worth $18 million with the [[Florida Panthers]] on July 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL Free Agent Tracker|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/feature/?id=25880|work=The Sports Network|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the final year of his contract with the Panthers in the [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315 season]], and with his offensive production having declined each season with Florida, Fleischmann was traded to the [[Anaheim Ducks]] in exchange for [[Dany Heatley]] and a [[2015 NHL Entry Draft|2015]] third-round draft pick on February 28, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=755657 | title = Panthers trade Fleischmann to Ducks for Heatley, Pick | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2015-02-28 | accessdate = 2015-03-01}}</ref> Fleischmann played a complementary role within the Ducks organization, finishing the regular season with 6 points in 14 games. In the post-season, Fleischmann was relegated to a depth role and healthy scratch in appearing only 6 post-season games with the Conference finalist Ducks.\n\nAs an un-signed free agent in the off-season, on September 12, 2015, Fleischmann accepted an invite on a professional try-out contract with the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=778831 | title = Canadiens invite Fleischmann to camp on tryout | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = 2015-09-12 | accessdate = 2015-09-12}}</ref>  On October 4, 2015, the Canadiens signed Fleischmann to a one-year,  $750,000 contract. In the [[2015-16 NHL season|2015\u201316]] season, Fleischmann contributed to the Canadiens early unbeaten success, regaining his offensive presence while featuring on the third-line. Fleischmann compiled 10 goals and 10 assists in 57 games with the Canadiens before he was traded to the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] along with teammate [[Dale Weise]] in exchange for a 2018 second round draft pick and [[Phillip Danault]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/canadiens-trade-weise-fleischmann-to-blackhawks-for-danault-and-a-pick/ | title = Canadiens trade Weise, Fleischmann to Blackhawks for Danault and a pick | publisher = [[Sportsnet.ca]] | date = 2016-02-26 | accessdate = 2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Fleischmann was signed by the [[Minnesota Wild]] to a professional try-out contract, unfortunately, on September 25, 2016, he was released from by the Wild after failing his physical. Although with his history of blood clots, the Wild did not disclose the injury out of respect for Fleischmann's privacy.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.twincities.com/2016/09/23/wild-tomas-fleischmann-fails-physical/ | title = Tomas Fleischmann fails physical | publisher = [[TwinCities.com]] | date = 2016-09-23 | accessdate = 2016-09-23}}</ref> Fleischmann later returned to the Florida area with his family, and unofficially began his post playing career by tentatively coaching at the [[Florida Panthers]] youth hockey clinics throughout the [[2016-17 NHL season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref>{{cite web| url =  https://www.nhl.com/panthers/news/fleischmann-finds-joy-in-panthers-hockey-clinics/c-286827496 | title = Fleischmann finds joy in Panthers Hockey Clinics | publisher = [[Florida Panthers]] | date = 2017-02-17 | accessdate = 2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==International play==\n{{MedalTableTop| name = no}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ih|CZE}} }}\n{{MedalSport | [[Ice hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IIHF World U18 Championships|IIHF U18 Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2002 IIHF World U18 Championships|2002 Pie\u0161\u0165any]] | }}\n{{MedalBottom\n}}\nFleischmann first represented the [[Czech Republic men's national ice hockey team|Czech Republic]] during his final junior year in the Czech Republic when he was named to the [[2002 IIHF World U18 Championships|2002]] World Under 18 Championship squad. In eight games in Slovakia, Fleischmann scored one goal and two assists as the Czech Republic defeated [[Finland men's national ice hockey team|Finland]] 4\u20132 to capture the bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/0102/W18/gs/pg000057.htm | title = Czech Rep team statistics | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref>\n\nWhile with the Moose Jaw Warriors, Fleischmann earned consecutive selections in the Czech [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championship]] squad's for [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2003]] and [[2004 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2004]] respective sixth and fourth-place finishes.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.iihf.com/Hydra/Tournaments/output/W20/hydra.iihf.com/data/iihf/output/xml/6/IHM0060CZE_33_11_0.pdf | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15 | title = Czech Republic Team Roster }}</ref> In 13 combined games, Fleischmann posted four goals and two assists.\n\nAfter completing his first professional season with the Capitals in 2007\u201308, Fleischmann was added to his first senior Czech squad at the [[2008 IIHF World Championship|2008]] World Championships in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.iihf.com/channels/iihf-world-championship/teams/cze.html | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2010-11-15 | accessdate = 2010-11-15 | title = 2008 Czech World Championship roster }}</ref> Fleischmann scored his first senior goal in a 5\u20130 shutout round-robin win over [[Switzerland men's national ice hockey team|Switzerland]] on May 8, 2008.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://reports.iihf.hockey/Hydra/132/IHM132E27_74_3_0.pdf | title =CZE 5, SUI 0 | publisher = [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] | date = 2008-05-08 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref> He completed the tournament with five points in seven games as the Czechs finished in fifth place.\n\nAs a part of the Capitals' highest scoring team in 2009\u201310, Fleischmann was selected mid-season to the Czech team for the [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2010 Winter Olympics]] on December 30, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=511663 | title = Tomas Fleischmann named to Czech Republic's Olympic Team | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] |date = 2009-12-30 | accessdate = 2010-11-15}}</ref> Fleischmann scored three points in five games for the Czech Republic en route to a disappointing seventh-place finish.\n\n== Career statistics ==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season]] \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]] \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! [[Season (sports)|Season]] \n! Team \n! League \n! GP \n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] \n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] \n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] \n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]] \n! GP \n! G \n! A \n! Pts \n! PIM \n|- \n| 2000\u201301\n| [[HC V\u00edtkovice]]\n| CZE U20\n| 21\n| 4\n| 9\n| 13\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2001\u201302\n| HC V\u00edtkovice\n| CZE U20\n| 44\n| 25\n| 25\n| 50\n| 16\n| 2\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| 2001\u201302\n| HC Nov\u00fd Ji\u010d\u00edn\n| [[2nd Czech Republic Hockey League|CZE.3]]\n| 8\n| 3\n| 2\n| 5\n| 8\n| 7\n| 3\n| 4\n| 7\n| 35\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2002\u201303 WHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| [[Moose Jaw Warriors]]\n| [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n| 65\n| 21\n| 50\n| 71\n| 36\n| 12\n| 4\n| 11\n| 15\n| 6\n|-  \n| [[2003\u201304 WHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| Moose Jaw Warriors\n| WHL\n| 60\n| 33\n| 42\n| 75\n| 32\n| 10\n| 3\n| 4\n| 7\n| 10\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2004\u201305 AHL season|2004\u201305]]\n| [[Portland Pirates]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 53\n| 7\n| 12\n| 19\n| 14\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Hershey Bears]]\n| AHL\n| 57\n| 30\n| 33\n| 63\n| 32\n| 20\n| 11\n| 21\n| 32\n| 15\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Washington Capitals]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 14\n| 0\n| 2\n| 2\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[2006\u201307 AHL season|2006\u201307]]\n| Hershey Bears\n| AHL\n| 45\n| 22\n| 29\n| 51\n| 22\n| 19\n| 5\n| 16\n| 21\n| 10\n|- bgcolor=\"#